SG90 servoları ve PCA9685 modülü 5V ile çalışır.

Özetle, 8 adet SG90 servoyu eş zamanlı olarak bir PCA9685 servo kontrol modülü ile çalıştırmak için şunlara ihtiyacınız olacaktır:

En az 7A (7.000mA) akım sağlayabilen bir güç kaynağı, 5V'ta.
Yüksek akım yüklerini kaldırabilecek kablolama ve bağlantılar, voltaj düşüşlerini en aza indirmek için uygun kablo kalınlıkları.
Güç kaynağı ve PCA9685 modülü için uygun ısı dağıtımı ve havalandırma, yüksek akımlar ısı üretebilir.


Certainly! Here are the specific current and amperage numbers you would need to consider when running 8 SG90 servos with a PCA9685 servo controller module:

Current Draw per SG90 Servo:

Stall Current: Approximately 800mA (0.8A) per servo at maximum load
Typical Operating Current: Around 200mA (0.2A) per servo with no load
Total Current Draw for 8 SG90 Servos:

Stall Current: 8 servos x 800mA = 6,400mA (6.4A)
Typical Operating Current: 8 servos x 200mA = 1,600mA (1.6A)
PCA9685 Module Current Draw:

The PCA9685 module itself typically draws around 10mA (0.01A) of current.
Recommended Power Supply Current Rating:
To account for the maximum possible current draw and provide some headroom, it is recommended to use a power supply with a current rating of at least 7A (7,000mA) or higher.

Voltage Requirements:

The SG90 servos and the PCA9685 module operate at 5V.
So, in summary, to run 8 SG90 servos simultaneously with a PCA9685 servo controller module, you would need:

A power supply capable of providing at least 7A (7,000mA) of current at 5V.
Wiring and connections capable of handling the high current loads, with appropriate wire gauges to minimize voltage drops.
Proper heat dissipation and ventilation for the power supply and PCA9685 module, as high currents can generate significant heat.
It's important to note that these numbers represent the maximum current draw scenario when all 8 servos are operating at stall conditions (maximum load). In typical use cases, the current draw may be lower, but it's always better to have a power supply with sufficient headroom to account for peak loads and ensure reliable operation.

Additionally, it's recommended to distribute the load across multiple servo movements and avoid simultaneous high-speed movements of all servos to reduce the peak current draw and potential strain on the power supply.

Source : Claude-3-Sonnet
